_ethn_group><wbmd_c_tm_of_yr_group><wbmd_c_tm_of_yr></wbmd_c_tm_of_yr></wbmd_c_tm_of_yr_group><wbmd_c_clncl_tgt_pop_group><wbmd_c_clncl_tgt_pop></wbmd_c_clncl_tgt_pop></wbmd_c_clncl_tgt_pop_group><wbmd_c_art_thmbnl></wbmd_c_art_thmbnl><wbmd_c_channel_id object_type="wbmd_lookup" wbmd_lookup_type="consumer_channel_id" wbmd_storage_val="1032" wbmd_disp_nm="Depression"></wbmd_c_channel_id><wbmd_c_frnd_nm>Comparing-Symptoms-of-Normal-Moodiness-With-Depression-in-Children-Topic</wbmd_c_frnd_nm><wbmd_c_asset_name></wbmd_c_asset_name><wbmd_c_teaser></wbmd_c_teaser><wbmd_c_mini_article object_type="wbmd_cons_shrt_txt" directive="expand" chronic_id="0000000000000000"></wbmd_c_mini_article></metadata_section><content_section><cons_import_health_ref><title>Topic Overview</title><pages><page><section_group><section_header></section_header><section_type>SpecialSection</section_type><section_text><p>It is normal for your growing child to be moody or somewhat irritable
		as he or she moves through adolescence. But symptoms of prolonged sadness or
		irritability and a loss of pleasure in activities the child enjoyed before can
		point to <a chronic_id="091e9c5e80732fb0" crossLinkId="65" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e80732fb0" href="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Depression Health Center_091e9c5e80732fb0/page_Depression Health Center_091e9c5e80732fb0.xml" keywordId="7244" keywordSetId="1082" object_type="wbmd_pb_page" path="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Depression Health Center_091e9c5e80732fb0/page_Depression Health Center_091e9c5e80732fb0.xml">depression</a>. Depression is not a normal part of growing up. Deciding
		whether your child's behavior is normal or a symptom of depression can be
		difficult.</p><p>A family history of
		<a chronic_id="091e9c5e801071dc" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="Definition" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/depression_in_children_and_teens_definition_za1266.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/depression_in_children_and_teens_definition_za1266.xml">depression</a>,
		<a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001b3ef" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="Definition" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/substance_abuse_definition_sts17238.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/substance_abuse_definition_sts17238.xml">substance abuse</a>, or
		<a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001b059" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="Definition" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/anxiety_definition_sta14104.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/anxiety_definition_sta14104.xml">anxiety</a> increases your child's risk for depression. A child is also more likely to become depressed if a parent is
		depressed.</p><p>Your child may need to be evaluated for depression if he or
		she:</p><ul><li>Is continuously sad or irritable, and not just
		 with parents, but even with friends.</li><li>Is sad or irritable without a
		 known trigger (no recent experience, such as being rejected by peers, caused
		 the mood change).</li><li>Shows no pleasure with friendships or activities
		 enjoyed in the past, such as sports or hobbies.</li><li>Doesn't ask for added
		 privileges, such as driving the car or going out with friends on a school
		 night.</li><li>Displays unprovoked or unexplained anger or <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8003c115" crossLinkId="452" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8003c115" href="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Anxiety and Panic Disorders Health Center TOC/page_Anxiety and Panic Disorders Health Center_091e9c5e8003c115.xml" keywordId="31072" keywordSetId="8074" object_type="wbmd_pb_page" path="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Anxiety and Panic Disorders Health Center TOC/page_Anxiety and Panic Disorders Health Center_091e9c5e8003c115.xml">anxiety</a>,
		 especially in a preadolescent.</li><li>Complains of symptoms such as
		 <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8002394a" crossLinkId="189" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8002394a" href="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/MigrainesHeadaches Health Center/page_Migraines and Headaches Health Center_091e9c5e8002394a.xml" keywordId="7521" keywordSetId="1291" object_type="wbmd_pb_page" path="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/MigrainesHeadaches Health Center/page_Migraines and Headaches Health Center_091e9c5e8002394a.xml">headache</a> or <a chronic_id="091e9c5e800079f8" crossLinkId="1553434" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e800079f8" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/digestive_disorders/miscellaneous/digestive_diseases_abdominal_pain.xml" keywordId="62949" keywordSetId="7962" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/digestive_disorders/miscellaneous/digestive_diseases_abdominal_pain.xml">stomach pain</a> that have no physical cause.</li><li>Breaks down
		 crying often and doesn't know why.</li><li>Has a sudden, noticeable
		 decrease in school performance.</li></ul><p>Most children will experience some unexplained sadness or boredom now and then. Asking your child a few questions about how he or she is feeling
		overall may help identify mild or moderate depression, which is more difficult
		to recognize than symptoms of severe depression. Some examples of questions to
		ask your child to help you decide if your child needs to see a health
		professional for possible depression might include:</p><ul><li>Do you feel angry most of the
		 time?</li><li>Do you feel sad every day?</li><li>Do you laugh with your
		 friends?</li><li>Do you feel happy when you are doing things you enjoy,
		 like a favorite hobby or a sport?</li><li>Do you feel like you get upset
		 easily and you don't know why?</li><li>Do you stay sad or mad for a long
		 time?</li></ul><p>While questions such as these will not diagnose depression, they can
		open the doors of communication with your child and help you decide whether
		your child needs to be further assessed by a health professional.</p></section_text></section_group></page></pages><citations></citations><related_links_type></related_links_type><related_links_header></related_links_header><related_links_text></related_links_text></cons_import_health_ref></content_section></wbmd_asset></content><friendlyurls><target siteid="3" name="WebMD" issearchable="true" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/comparing-symptoms-of-normal-moodiness-with-depression-in-children-topic" owner="false"><breadcrumb><bread piece="A to Z Guides" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/default.htm"></bread></breadcrumb><centers><Topic id="1143" name="tmg" chronicid="091e9c5e807f0e57" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/comparing-symptoms-of-normal-moodiness-with-depression-in-children-topic" type="Topic">Comparing Symptoms of Normal Moodiness With Depression in Children</Topic></centers></target><target siteid="8" name="WebMD_Mobile" issearchable="true" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/tc/comparing-symptoms-of-normal-moodiness-with-depression-in-children-topic" owner="false"><breadcrumb><bread piece="A to Z Guides" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/default.htm"></bread><bread piece="Related Topics" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/tc/default.htm"></bread></breadcrumb><centers><Topic id="11198" name="tmg" chronicid="091e9c5e807f0e57" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/tc/comparing-symptoms-of-normal-moodiness-with-depression-in-children-topic" type="Topic">Comparing Symptoms of Normal Moodiness With Depression in Children</Topic></centers></target></friendlyurls><referenced_objects><object chronic_id="091e9c5e80732fb0" thmbnl="" pointer="0" path="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Depression Health Center_091e9c5e80732fb0/page_Depression Health Center_091e9c5e80732fb0.wxml"><target siteid="3" name="WebMD" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/depression/default.htm" umtchronicleid="091e9c5e806934ca"></targ